  "prompt": "Why isn't the Moon spinning?",
  "response": "The Moon does spin; however, it spins at the same rate that it orbits the Earth. This phenomenon is called **synchronous rotation** or **tidally locked rotation**. \n\nHere\u2019s how it works:\n1. The Moon rotates on its own axis, just like the Earth.\n2. It takes the Moon about **27.3 days** to complete one full rotation on its axis.\n3. Coincidentally, it also takes the Moon about **27.3 days** to orbit the Earth.\n\nBecause the rotation and orbital periods are the same, the Moon always keeps the same face pointed toward the Earth. This is why we only ever see one side of the Moon from Earth, giving the illusion that it doesn\u2019t spin.\n\n### Why is it tidally locked?\nThis synchronization is the result of **tidal forces** between the Earth and the Moon. Over billions of years, the gravitational interaction between the two bodies caused the Moon's rotation to slow down until it matched its orbital period. This is a common occurrence for many moons in our solar system.\n\n### So, is the Moon spinning?\nYes, but its spin is perfectly synchronized with its orbit, making it appear stationary from our perspective on Earth.",
